{{Infobox video game | title = Control | image = File:Control cover art.jpg | caption = Promotional artwork featuring protagonist Jesse Faden | developer = [[Remedy Entertainment]] | publisher = [[505 Games]] | engine = | director = {{Unbulleted list|Mikael Kasurinen|[[Sam Lake]]}} | producer = | designer = | programmer = | artist = | writer = {{Unbulleted list|Sam Lake|Anna Megill}} | composer = | series = | platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]}} | released = 2019 | genre = [[Third-person shooter]], [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] | modes = [[Single-player]] }}
'''''Control''''' is an upcoming [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[third-person shooter]] developed by [[Remedy Entertainment]] and published by [[505 Games]]. ''Control'' is set to be released in 2019 for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]].
==Gameplay== Like Remedy's previous projects, ''Control'' is played from a [[third-person perspective]]. In the game, players fight against enemies using The Director's Pistol, which is a firearm which can be transformed into different shapes. The pistol can also be upgraded to enhance its combat efficiency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/11/17452006/control-reveal-trailer-e3-2018-remedy-quantum-break|title=Control is a time-bending new game from the developers of Quantum Break|first=Chaim|last=Gartenberg|date=June 11, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018|work=[[The Verge]]}}</ref> In addition, players will have access to various supernatural and telekinetic abilities. For instance, she can use debris to form a defensive shield and hurl objects towards enemies, using them as weapons. Players can acquire Objects of Power by completing [[side quest]]s or exploring the game's world. They are items which can be used to unlock new skills, such as the ability for Jesse to levitate in air.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2018-alan-wake-devs-new-game-is-unbridled-actio/1100-6459798/|title=E3 2018: Alan Wake Dev's New Game Is Unbridled Action Driven By Dream Logic|first=Peter|last=Brown|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> Remedy added that the game is less linear than its previous games and that players would have plenty of opportunities to explore.<ref name="official">{{cite web|url=https://www.remedygames.com/announcing-control-a-new-remedy-game/|title=Announcing Control, a new Remedy game|first=Thomas|last=Puha|publisher=[[Remedy Entertainment]]|date=June 13, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> In an interview with [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] in December 2016, Kasurinen said the game would feature [[cooperative gameplay]],<ref name="coop"/> but Remedy has since confirmed that ''Control'' will be a single-player game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.remedygames.com/announcing-control-a-new-remedy-game/|title=Announcing Control, a new Remedy game - Remedy|date=2018-06-12|work=Remedy|access-date=2018-06-21|language=en-US}}</ref> ==Synopsis== ===Setting=== ''Control'' takes place primarily within the Oldest House, a featureless, [[Brutalist]] skyscraper in Manhattan that acts as the headquarters of the Federal Bureau of Control, a secretive government organization that deals with unexplained or supernatural phenomena. The FBC's goal is to study, contain, and, if possible, seize control of supernatural elements and manipulate them for their own purposes, often regardless of moral considerations. The Oldest House itself acts as the main setting of ''Control'' and is a supernatural place of power, where the FBC contains various Altered Items, objects which have been acted upon by supernatural forces. The Oldest House's topography is constantly shifting, and its interior is vastly larger than its exterior. The FBC has developed ritualistic processes which can alter the Oldest House in certain ways, allowing one to potentially travel infinitely deeper into it, gradually leaving our ordinary reality behind. ===Plot=== After a traumatic childhood experience grants her unexplained supernatural powers, Jesse Faden (Courtney Hope) seeks answers at the Federal Bureau of Control, a clandestine government agency tasked with studying and containing supernatural phenomena. After the Bureau's headquarters, the Oldest House, is invaded by an otherworldly force known only as the Hiss, Jesse is thrust into the role of Director of the FBC via a strange, ritualistic process. Now, haunted by the ghostly remnants of former Director Zachariah Trench ([[James McCaffrey (actor)|James McCaffrey]]), Jesse must find her way through the ever-shifting halls of the Oldest House in order to defeat the Hiss and uncover the answers she seeks.<ref name="IGNPre">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/06/13/e3-2018-control-is-like-a-supernatural-quantum-break|title=E3 2018: Control is Like A Supernatural Quantum Break|first=Ryan|last=McCaffery|work=[[IGN]]|date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>
==Development== The game is being developed by [[Remedy Entertainment]]. Mikael Kasurinen, who has worked on Remedy's previous project, ''[[Quantum Break]]'', is the game's director and [[Sam Lake]] served as the game's writer and creative director.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/07/05/remedys-sam-lake-on-21-years-of-game-storytelling-and-transmedia/|title=Remedy’s Sam Lake on 21 years of game storytelling and transmedia|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=July 5, 2017|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/index.php/e3-2018/2018/06/11/remedy-announces-gravity-bending-shooter-control|title=Remedy Announces Gravity-Bending Shooter, Control|first=Brian|last=Shea|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=June 11, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> Development of the game began before the release of ''Quantum Break'', and as of May 2017, the game was still in preproduction.<ref name="life after xbox">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-05-25-not-the-finnish-remedys-new-age|title=Remedy on life after Xbox exclusivity|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=May 26, 2017|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> ''Control'' is powered by the Northlight engine, which was utilized in ''Quantum Break''.<ref name="IGNPre"/>
Instead of focusing on creating a large and complex story, the game's writers put more emphasis on creating a game world and universe that is rich enough for players to craft their own stories.<ref name="life after xbox"/> Another goal for the team was to create a game that has high replayability.<ref name="life after xbox"/> Lake assured players that the game will feature a strong narrative, one that is "narrowly focused" according to Kasurinen.<ref name="coop">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/features/2016/12/28/14101058/remedy-new-game-p7|title=Why Alan Wake's creators want to make you the storyteller|first=Brian|last=Crecente|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=December 18, 2016|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>
In May 2017, Remedy announced that they had partnered with [[505 Games]] to publish the game, then codenamed "P7". 505 provided marketing and publishing support and a fund of €7.75 million to assist the game's development, while Remedy retained the [[intellectual property]] rights to ''Control''. In the press release, Remedy revealed that the game will have complex gameplay mechanics and that it will be a "longer term experience" than its previous games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-05-03-505-games-will-publish-remedy-entertainments-new-game|title=505 Games will publish Remedy Entertainment's new game|first=Matthew|last=Handrahan|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=May 3, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> ''P7'' was being worked on by Remedy alongside two other projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/remedys-upcoming-third-person-action-game-codenamed-p7-will-be-out-in-2019/|title=Remedy's upcoming third-person action game, codenamed P7, will be out in 2019|first=Samuel|last=Horti|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=February 18, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> The game was officially revealed at [[Sony Interactive Entertainment]]'s [[E3 2018]] press conference.<ref name="release date">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/396643-e3-2018-new-remedy-game-control|title=E3 2018: New Remedy Game Control Announced at Sony Conference|first=Bradley|last=Russell|work=[[Game Revolution]]|date=June 11, 2018|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> It will be Remedy's first game on a Sony platform since 2003's ''[[Max Payne 2: The Fall of Max Payne]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-04-11-remedy-eyes-ps4-development-after-20-percent-revenue-rise|title=Remedy eyes PS4 development after 20% revenue rise|first=Matthew|last=Handrahan|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=April 11, 2017|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref> ''Control'' is set to be released for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] in 2019.<ref name="release date"/>
