[[Image:Kosanji Hondo.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Kōsan-ji [[Main Hall (Japanese Buddhism)|Hondō]]]]

{{nihongo|'''Kōsan-ji'''|耕三寺}} is a [[Hongan-ji]] school [[Jōdo Shinshū]] [[Buddhist temples in Japan|temple]] on the island of Ikuchijima in [[Onomichi, Hiroshima|Onomichi]], [[Hiroshima Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. Founded by the industrialist Koso Kōsanji in 1936 in honour of his deceased mother, and with an area of approximately fifty thousand square metres, many of its structures are modelled upon the country's most famous historic temples and shrines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.onomichi.hiroshima.jp/english/kanko/data_setoda/t_kousan.html |title=Kosanji Temple and Museum |publisher=[[Onomichi, Hiroshima|Onomichi City]] |accessdate=19 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721165032/http://www.city.onomichi.hiroshima.jp/english/kanko/data_setoda/t_kousan.html |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The Miraishin no Oka is a monument landscaped with five thousand square metres of [[Carrara marble]], weighing some three thousand tons, by Kazuto Kuetani.<ref>{{cite book |title=Faith and Power in Japanese Buddhist Art, 1600-2005 |author=Graham, Patricia J. |publisher=[[University of Hawaii Press]] |pages=248–50, 230–33 |year=2007 |ISBN=978-0-8248-3126-4}}</ref> The Kōsan-ji Museum houses over two thousand items, including nineteen [[Important Cultural Properties of Japan|Important Cultural Properties]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kousanji.or.jp/e6kousan.htm |title=Choseizan Kosanji Temple |publisher=Kōsanji |accessdate=19 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703070502/http://www.kousanji.or.jp/e6kousan.htm |archivedate=3 July 2011 |df= }}</ref>

